<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910719-0158</DOCNO><DOCID>910719-0158.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Industrial Espionage Case   Entangles Japanese Firms</HL><DATE>07/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   HIT J.KMT J.MHI J.TUM</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)HEAVY MACHINERY, FARM EQUIPMENT (MAC)</IN><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Police sent officers yesterday to MitsubishiHeavy Industries Ltd. and a unit of Hitachi Ltd. inconnection with a widening case of alleged industrial spying.   The case surfaced Wednesday when officials at Toyo UnpankiCo., a small machinery maker in Osaka, acknowledged that theypaid for documents allegedly stolen from Komatsu Ltd., theworld's second-largest maker of construction machinery.</LP><TEXT>   Tokyo police asked Mitsubishi Heavy to provide documentsrelated to the leaking of Komatsu information. Police tookone box of documents. A spokeswoman for Mitsubishi Heavyconfirmed that police spent more than two hours at companyheadquarters, but wouldn't comment on the contents of the boxor whether Mitsubishi Heavy ever paid for documents relatingto Komatsu.   Police also went yesterday to Hitachi ConstructionMachinery Co., a 52.7%-owned unit of Hitachi. A spokesmansaid he could not discuss what police were searching for orwhat, if anything, was taken in the search.   Japanese press reports said police went to 14 companiesyesterday, including Mitsubishi Heavy and the Hitachi unit,to search for information related to the scandal. The Tokyopolice wouldn't confirm any of the reports.   The searches followed the arrest Wednesday of KiyoshiOhta, 51, on suspicions of breaking into a Tokyo-basedcompany, stealing documents and selling them to a competingconcern. Mr. Ohta is suspected of stealing vital documents onmarketing and product development from Komatsu and sellingthem to Toyo Unpanki for 10 million yen. Mr. Ohta also toldpolice he sold information on Komatsu to about 10 companies,local press reports said.   Komatsu, based in Tokyo, filed a complaint with the Tokyopolice last December about a theft of &quot;top secret materialsrelated to the development and marketing of constructionmachinery.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>